The Recurrence Chancery was the Void Citadel's adjudicative loop-office where testimony could be re-entered, reframed, and retried indefinitely.
The Citadel's institutional logic extended its loop-mechanics into legal process: a case was never closed, only re-opened at different parameters.
The Chancery operated on the principle that no verdict was final because conditions that produced the original dispute could always recur.
Petitioners filed initial claims through the intake warden; the Chancery clerk assigned a case a recurrence index indicating how many prior cycles it had undergone.
Cases with high recurrence indices were considered more complex, not more resolved — the assumption was that repeated trials deepened the record.
In practice, the Chancery produced a class of permanently litigating parties who could never exit the system because the system had no exit condition.
Post-Citadel scholars describe the Chancery as the legal expression of the Citadel's core pathology: an institution designed for process, not outcome.
Its records — where they survive — are notable for their completeness: every re-entry, every reframing, every partial verdict is documented.
The completeness is the horror: a system that documented its own dysfunction with perfect thoroughness.
The Chancery's structure influenced some Midgaard legal theorists who found in it a cautionary model for testimony-loop prevention.
No active institution claims direct succession from the Recurrence Chancery; several claim to have solved its defining flaw.

